Assuming you have a Map class with the following properties:

```c#
public class Map {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Size { get; set; }
}
```

You can create a new class with the same properties:

```c#
public class NewObject {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Size { get; set; }
}
```

And then use LINQ to convert the Map list to NewObject list:

```c#
List<Map> mapList = new List<Map>
{
    new Map { Id = 1, Name = "Map 1",  Size = 100 },
    new Map { Id = 2, Name = "Map 2",  Size = 200 },
    new Map { Id = 3, Name = "Map 3",  Size = 300 }
};

List<NewObject> newObjectList = mapList.Select(x => new NewObject {
    Id = x.Id,
    Name = x.Name,
    Size = x.Size
}).ToList();
```

This will create a new list called `newObjectList` with the same number of elements as `mapList` and each element in the new list will have the same values for the Id, Name and Size properties as the corresponding element in the Map list.

